@l0rd PTAL

The hard coded path should be removed. I don't think qemu would matter even, does it? The gvproxy binary is looked up using FindHelperBinary() so the installer would need to put it in the right places.

Given we can only compile hard coded paths I guess the only logical solution would be for the machine installer to create the containers.conf file with helper_binaries_dir set to the right install location?

The hard-coded path should be removed. It's a leftover.

Instead of delegating the config to the installer, we can use `FindHelperBinary` that can look in the podman.exe folder if we specify `$BINDIR`:

```golang
var defaultHelperBinariesDir = []string{
	// Relative to the binary directory
	"$BINDIR",
} 
```

We should also use this opportunity to fix a WSL inconsistency. The WSL code doesn't call `FindHelperBinary` (note how [StartNetworking](https://github.com/containers/podman/blob/7958d910aab2fbdcc05eb701955dad706594c40e/pkg/machine/shim/networking.go#L104) is called before `FindHelperBinary` and the `gvproxy.GvproxyCommand` parameter is null). The `gvproxy`/`winssh-proxy` path is retrieved using `FindExecutablePeer` (that looks in `podman.exe` folder).
